04369nam a22006975i 9780674033849DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20092008mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740338497 a10.4159/97806740338492doi  a(DE-B1597)644681  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQ127.T28bG74 2008 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a338.95124/9062221 aGreene, J. Megan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Origins of the Developmental State in Taiwan :bScience Policy and the Quest for Modernization /cJ. Megan Greene. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2009] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (238 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations and Note on Romanization -- tIntroduction: Science Policy in a Developmental State -- t1 Starts and Stops: The Kuomintang and Science and Technology -- t2 The First Push: Domestic and Foreign Advocates -- t3 The State Gets Interested: The Lure of Economic Development -- t4 Coordinating Policy: Manpower Planning and Education -- t5 The Final Step: The State Comes Together -- tConclusion: Is Taiwan’s Past China’s Future? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe rapid growth of Taiwan’s postwar “miracle” economy is most frequently credited to the leading role of the state in promoting economic development. Megan Greene challenges this standard interpretation in the first in-depth examination of the origins of Taiwan’s developmental state. Greene examines the ways in which the Guomindang state planned and promoted scientific and technical development both in mainland China between 1927 and 1949 and on Taiwan after 1949. Using industrial science policy as a lens, she shows that the state, even during its most authoritarian periods, did not function as a monolithic entity. State planners were concerned with maximizing the use of Taiwan’s limited resources for industrial development. Political leaders, on the other hand, were most concerned with the state’s political survival. The developmental state emerged gradually as a result of the combined efforts of technocrats and outsiders, including academicians and foreign advisors. Only when the political leadership put its authority and weight behind the vision of these early planners did Taiwan’s developmental state fully come into being. In Taiwan’s combination of technocratic expertise and political authoritarianism lie implications for our understanding of changes taking place in mainland China today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aScience and statezChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aScience and statezChina. 0aScience and statezTaiwanxHistoryy20th century. 0aScience and statezTaiwan. 0aTechnology and statezChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aTechnology and statezChina. 0aTechnology and statezTaiwanxHistoryy20th century. 0aTechnology and statezTaiwan. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674033849?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674033849423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674033849/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK